properties.Name: Julesberg Junction (tower demolished 1981)
properties.description: Chappell, NE was erected around 1980 and replaced the original Julesburg, CO tower which was 4-5 miles south of Julesburg next to US Highway 385. The Julesburg site was part of the original transcontinental radio relay route, but its tower was removed after the Chappell junction tower was built about 7 miles north of Julesburg. The new site eliminated reflection/interference problems which came into existence on the Ogallala-Julesburg hop after the I-80 or I-76 overpasses were constructed. The new tower is actually located ten miles east of Chappell on the north side of U.S. Highway 30 - or three miles north and one mile east of Nebraska Exit 95 on I-80. https://www.long-lines.net/places-routes/ChappellNE/index.html

properties.Name: Whiteface Mountain Peak NY (Temporary)
properties.description: This was the relay site for 1980 Lake Placid Winter Olympics. It linked the Whiteface Mountain venue (3K' below) and the Mt. VanHovensburg venue (to the south) to the Lake Placid Broadcast Center. It also relayed feeds from the broadcast center northeast to Plattsburg and then down the Hudson River valley chain to ABC headquarters in New York City. ABC also had an ENG microwave relay site here to handle several news vans brought in from its owned and operated stations around the US. This was especially helpful when the downtown Lake Placid venue production trucks experienced a power outage less than an hour before Eric Heiden competed for his final speed skating gold medal. The ENG trucks were able to provide basic coverage of the event. All equipment was brought in and set up the previous fall after the observation center closed for the season but before the onset of serious winter weather. AT&T and ABC crews were shuttled to and from the peak by Sikorsky S-58 helicopter if the road wasn't passable. (GMB 03/25/03)

properties.Name: Lake Placid NY Broadcast Center (Temporary)
properties.description: This site was used for the 1980 Lake Placid Winter Olympics. The building was built as the broadcast center and later converted to the town highway garage. It was linked by AT&T to the temporary site on Whiteface Mountain for incoming feeds from Mt. VanHovensburg  and Whiteface Mountain venues (production truck farms). The downtown Lake Placid venue for skating and ceremonies was linked by fiber as was the ski jump venue just up the road. An AT&T outgoing link was relayed by Whiteface Mountain to Plattsburgh and down the Hudson River chain to ABC NYC for domestic and international programming feeds. Dishes were placed on scaffolding alongside the building and connected to radios inside the building. The outgoing link was backed up by a mobile C-band satellite link to Long Island and into NYC by AT&T microwave. On at least one occasion terrestrial audio and video signals were intermixed with satellite signals resulting in audio that was 1/3 second ahead or behind the video.  (GMB 03/25/15)

properties.Name: Whiteface Mountain Venue NY (Temporary)
properties.description: This was the site of the production truck farm for the 1980 Lake Placid Winter Olympics Whiteface Mountain venue. All the downhill and slalom events were held at this venue. Camera and audio cables were run to the various vantage points during the prior summers; the morning of the event, cameras were picked up by a Sikorsky S-58 helicopter winch cable and flown to the required positions. There was a temporary outgoing AT&T microwave link to the top of the mountain and back to the broadcast center in Lake Placid. The dishes were placed on scaffolding and connected to radios in an adjacent trailer. ABC & AT&T trucks were towed up from base of the mountain with a bulldozer. There may also have been an incoming feed from Lake Placid. (GMB 03/25/15)

properties.Name: Mt VanHovensburg Venue NY (Temporary)
properties.description: This was the site of the production truck farm for the 1980 Lake Placid Winter Olympics Mt. VanHovensburg venue. The bob sled, luge, cross country and biathlon events were held at this venue. Camera and audio cables were run to the various vantage points during the prior summers; the morning of the event, cameras were picked up by a Sikorsky S-58 helicopter winch cable and flown to the required positions. There was a temporary outgoing AT&T microwave link to Whiteface Mountain and back to the broadcast center in Lake Placid. The dishes were placed on scaffolding and connected to radios in an adjacent trailer. There may also have been an incoming feed from Lake Placid. (GMB 03/25/15)

properties.Name: Polk City, FL
properties.description: Double towers! https://web.archive.org/web/20011223031547/http://www1.shore.net:80/~mfoster/Polk_City.htm An LCXR main station, definitely hardened. In conversation with one of the switch techs, I learned that all of the decontamination & anti-fallout systems (airlocks, exterior washdown, etc.) had all been removed about 12-18 months ago to make room for office space and because they're no longer needed. AT&T long distance still switches at the site. They're in the basement though, and I didn't get a chance to poke around down there. This site still has its MW tower and has active MW gear on it (at least, the equipment in the room labeled "Microwave Room" is all still powered up and looks live). The only horn on the tower that appears to be in use points NNW, more or less. Right across the street (FL Rt. 33) is an ex-GTE (I think, the signs were mostly gone) CO with a MW tower as well. That site (according to the local ATT people) has been abandoned as a manned location for about three or four years at least. Found a repeater hut exactly two miles south of the site on Rt. 33 (actually, just off 33 to the right on a cross street as you head south from the site). Running along FL Rt. 33 right in front of this site are FO runs belonging to AT&T, GTE/Verizon, Time-Warner, and LDDS.

Main Central Office. MTS Microwave tower in Winnipeg
On Sunday, September 30, 1956, MTS connected to the TCTS microwave network, from the new 85-foot (26 m) high microwave tower built at the Fort Rouge Exchange on Corydon Ave.,[6] which meant that Winnipeggers were now able to receive non-live CBC programming on CBWT the same day it was broadcast in Toronto, and Montreal.
